is it diffing' thing they do on the roads with there cars might cut down the
problem (and save some lives) maybe?

I don't do shift work and I am glad I don't actually when I hear about
accidents like this that occur in the night/ early morning. Sometimes lately
now I see the tyre marks on the main N-Roads road in circles so I know it
goes on regularly but are they being stopped at all or are they just allowed
to get on with it.

Its tough bringing up kids I am at the stage now where I have a teenager in
Secondary and a 12 year old girl in Primary and I do try and steer them in
the right direction but I sometimes think that being too heavy handed makes
you come across as worrying too much and coming across as boring whereas
with their friends it most probably is more exciting to do what they do
instead

- I mean I am always talking to my son about these accidents and everything
and he is a great lad (in my eyes) and comes across as sensible and as he
gets older and maybe gets into a car with other teenagers that he will
remember all what he has been told about belting up and not acting the eejit
but if the others in the car are acting like eejits and dangerous he is
hardly going to tell them all to put seatbelts on and the driver to drive
slowly and responsibly and the others in the car to stop mucking about and
sit down is he thinking about it realistically. It all has to do with who
they mix with I suppose and you cannot watch over them all the time.

